st: additional directions
tb: When the clergy and people assemble before the service, they may gather
  out of doors, in the parish house, in a former or neighboring place of
  worship, or in some other building. When convenient, the procession may
  go around the building(s) to be dedicated and then go to the principal
  door. Hymns or psalms may be used in procession.

tb: The use of portable musical instruments is suitable. When the weather is
  inclement, or other circumstances make it necessary, the Congregation
  may assemble inside the church; the Bishop, other clergy, and attendants
  will enter in procession through the principal door.
  When a new church is being consecrated, it may be desirable that sacred
  vessels, ornaments, and decorations be carried into the building in the
  procession. Such things as the deed for the property and the blueprint of
  the building(s), the keys, and the tools used in its construction may also be
  carried by appropriate persons.

pb:537
tb: The cross, signed on the threshold by the Bishop, may also be marked in
  lasting form (incised, painted, inlaid). In place of a pastoral staff, the foot
  of a processional cross may be used for the signing.

tb: Selected verses of psalms, hymns, or instrumental music may be used as
  the ministers move from one part of the church to another.

tb: At the dedication of the Font, children or other lay persons may be
  assigned the task of pouring the water.

tb: If one reading stand is to serve as both lectern and pulpit, only one of the
  prayers, and one of the versicles and responses, are used, followed by the
  words of dedication.

tb: At the dedication and consecration of an altar, the Oil of Chrism may
  appropriately be used to mark five crosses on the unadorned Altar Table,
  one each at the four corners and one in the center.

st: for the dedication of churches and chapels in special cases

tb: If the place of public worship is also to serve as a school or parish hall,
  or for some other suitable purpose, the liturgy may be adapted to the
  circumstances, with the Bishop’s permission.

tb: If the church is also to be used for regular worship by other Christian
  bodies, it is appropriate that their representatives take part in the service,
  and that the service be adapted.

tb: When buildings have been used for public worship over many years
  without having been consecrated, consecration and dedication are
  appropriate. Furnishings already dedicated are not set apart again.

pb:538
st: secularization of a building previously consecrated and dedicated

r: The altar(s) and all consecrated and dedicated objects that are to be preserved are
  removed from the building prior to the service.
r: The Bishop, or a Minister appointed by the Bishop, begins with these or similar words

tb: We who are gathered here know that this building which
  has been set apart for the ministry of God’s holy Word and
  Sacraments will no longer be dedicated to this use [or will
  be taken down]. We thank Almighty God for all that he has
  accomplished here.

r: The Declaration of Secularization is now read.
l: In the Name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit. **Amen.**

tb: On the ___5___ day of ___5___, in the year of our Lord
  ___5___, at the hands of _N.N._, Bishop of ___8___, this
  building was duly consecrated and dedicated [in honor of
  ___11___]. The Sentence of Consecration has been in effect
  until this date.

tb: I, _N.N._, Bishop of ___8___, do hereby revoke the said
  Sentence, and do remit this building, and all the objects
  remaining in it, for any lawful and reputable use, according to
  the laws of this land.

tb: This building, having now been declared deconsecrated and
  secularized, I declare to be no longer subject to my canonical
  jurisdiction or that of this Church.

pb:539
tb: This Declaration is given under my hand and seal, in the City of
  ___8___, State/Province/Commonwealth of ___11___,
  in the Year of our Lord ___5___. (Signed) ___11___

r: The service concludes with the Lord’s Prayer and such other prayers, including the
  following litany, as the Bishop may direct.

st: a litany of thanksgiving for a church

tb: Let us thank God whom we worship here in the beauty of holiness.
tb: Eternal God, the heaven of heavens cannot contain you, much
  less the walls of temples made with hands. Graciously receive
  our thanks for this place, and accept the work of our hands,
  offered to your honor and glory.

l: For the Church universal, of which these visible buildings are a symbol,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.
l: For your presence whenever two or three have gathered together in your Name,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.
l: For this place where we may be still and know that you are God,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.
l: For making us your children by adoption and grace, and refreshing us day by day with the bread of life.
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.
l: For the knowledge of your will and the grace to perform it,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.
l: For the fulfilling of our desires and petitions as you see best for us,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.

pb:540
l: For the pardon of our sins, which restores us to the company of your faithful people,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.
l: For the blessing of our vows and the crowning of our years with your goodness,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.
l: For the faith of those who have gone before us and for our encouragement by their perseverance,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.

l: For the fellowship of [N., our patron, and of ] all your saints,
l:i:b: We thank you, Lord.

r:This Litany may be used on the anniversary of the consecration or dedication of a
  church, or on other suitable occasions, in which case the Celebrant concludes with
  the following Doxology.
v:celebrant: Yours, O Lord, is the greatness, and the power, and
v: the glory, and the victory, and the majesty: for every-
v: thing in heaven and on earth is yours; yours is the
v: kingdom, O Lord, and you are exalted as Head above
v: all. All things come from you, O Lord,
v:people: And of your own have we given you.
ref: 1 chronicles 29:11, 14 t
